Not even our emotional life is static.

215
00:17:40,909 --> 00:17:41,809
It's always changing.

216
00:17:42,250 --> 00:17:44,133
And we have a power.

217
00:17:44,192 --> 00:17:47,518
This is the whole point of moving into habits.

218
00:17:47,557 --> 00:17:49,381
We have a power to change ourselves.

219
00:17:49,421 --> 00:17:50,382
This is the point.

220
00:17:51,458 --> 00:17:57,303
So we've talked a little bit about concepts and perceptions and this word, our perception of how things change.

221
00:18:00,625 --> 00:18:13,277
Even on a wider scale of society, you know, there was a time in this country where if you insulted the monarch, l'es majesté, well, you could be, you could have your head chopped off.

222
00:18:13,297 --> 00:18:20,182
And there was a time you could actually, you know, declare your desire for republicanism quite openly.

223
00:18:20,602 --> 00:18:24,486
even during the king or queen's appearance.

224
00:18:24,967 --> 00:18:26,028
But now you get arrested.

225
00:18:26,307 --> 00:18:30,071
So it just shows you how times change.

226
00:18:30,491 --> 00:18:31,292
You know that, don't you?

227
00:18:31,573 --> 00:18:40,162
There was the Republicans at Charles' coronation.

228
00:18:41,143 --> 00:18:43,065
They went and arrested them, for heaven's sake.

229
00:18:43,925 --> 00:18:46,548
That made world news.

230
00:18:46,588 --> 00:18:49,511
So then we come to habits.

231
00:18:50,942 --> 00:18:52,625
So these are sankharas.

232
00:18:52,865 --> 00:19:00,333
They are translated as volitional conditionings by which we mean this is what we have really the power to change and the power to grow.

233
00:19:00,553 --> 00:19:02,494
The power to get rid of when we don't want them.

234
00:19:03,855 --> 00:19:12,444
And we find what we found in our lives that we might have had a certain understanding which has produced a certain type of behavior.

235
00:19:13,086 --> 00:19:16,308
And then when you came across the Buddha's teaching you find yourself changing.

236
00:19:16,728 --> 00:19:24,588
That ability to change from one type of behavior to another is to do with our volitional conditionings.

237
00:19:25,069 --> 00:19:26,614
And this is our work.

238
00:19:26,673 --> 00:19:28,779
I mean, in terms of spiritual life, that's our work.

239
00:19:28,819 --> 00:19:32,931
Can't do much about our senses, but you can definitely do something about your...

240
00:19:35,644 --> 00:19:59,323
your habits so i want to read a little bit here from the discourses this is a discourse about two ascetics so there was some very strange ideas during the buddha's time which is probably equally strange to some of the stuff that you get these days but the idea was by these two ascetics was that they were in a sense trying to beat karma by being what they might be at some future time

241
00:19:59,624 --> 00:20:03,490
So they were practicing dog asceticism and cow asceticism.

242
00:20:04,311 --> 00:20:15,152
I don't know, there's a lot of humor in the discourses and you never know whether this is actually for real or not, but definitely it points to the fact that some people had some very strange practices.

243
00:20:16,397 --> 00:20:18,603
So there was Apunah, the son of the Kaleans.

244
00:20:19,263 --> 00:20:23,332
Now the Kaleans were actually on the opposite side of the Sakyas on that river.

245
00:20:23,491 --> 00:20:26,538
They almost got into a war over water rights.

246
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:28,782
It's interesting, isn't it?

247
00:20:28,803 --> 00:20:30,406
2,500 years ago they had water rights.

248
00:20:31,588 --> 00:20:34,474
And they would have been connected some way.

249
00:20:35,175 --> 00:20:37,461
They would have been very close as peoples, you know.

250
00:20:37,980 --> 00:20:47,472
Anyway, the son of Cileans was an ox duty ascetic and also Senea, who was a naked duty, dog duty ascetic, went to see the Blessed One.

251
00:20:48,253 --> 00:20:52,578
And Punna, the ox duty ascetic, paid homage to the Blessed One and sat down at one side.

252
00:20:53,160 --> 00:21:02,892
And while Senea, the naked dog ascetic, exchanged greetings with the Blessed One, and when the courteous and amiable talk was finished, he too sat down by the side and curled up like a dog.

253
00:21:04,103 --> 00:21:13,555
Now, when Punna, the ox, duty ascetic, sat down, he asked the Blessed One, Venerable Sir, this naked dog, duty ascetic, Senea, does what is hard.

254
00:21:13,575 --> 00:21:15,917
He eats his food when it is thrown on the ground.

255
00:21:17,339 --> 00:21:21,925
That dog duty has long been taken up for him, by him, and practiced by him.

256
00:21:22,086 --> 00:21:23,387
What will be his destination?

257
00:21:23,468 --> 00:21:25,330
What will be his future course?

258
00:21:25,990 --> 00:21:27,933
Enough, Punna, let it be, don't ask me.

259
00:21:29,534 --> 00:21:35,903
So the second time he goes through this rigmarole, please, you know, can you tell me what will happen to you?

260
00:21:35,923 --> 00:21:43,297
And the third time, Gunnar, the Oxford duty, said, ask the venerable sir, this naked dog beauty ascetic, and he does what he's hard to do.

261
00:21:43,317 --> 00:21:46,040
He eats his food when he's thrown on the ground.

262
00:21:46,020 --> 00:21:48,807
That dog duty has long been taken up by in practice.

263
00:21:48,847 --> 00:21:50,451
What will be his destination?

264
00:21:50,491 --> 00:21:51,694
What will be his future course?

265
00:21:51,795 --> 00:22:03,163
Well, Poonam, since I certainly cannot persuade you when you ask and I say enough, Poonam, let it be, do not ask, I shall therefore answer you.

266
00:22:03,482 --> 00:22:04,164
Hear, Poonam.

267
00:22:04,549 --> 00:22:26,337
someone develops the dog duty fully and unstintingly he develops the dog habit fully and unstintingly he develops the dog mind fully and unstintingly he develops dog behavior fully and unstintingly having done that on the dissolution of the body after death he reappears in the company of dogs

268
00:22:26,317 --> 00:22:37,468
But if his view is such that this is virtue or duty or asceticism or religious life, I shall become a great god or some lesser god, that is a wrong view.

269
00:22:37,508 --> 00:22:44,654
Now there are two destinations for one who has wrong view, I say, hell or the animal womb.

270
00:22:45,355 --> 00:22:53,202
So puna, if his dog duty is perfected, it will lead him to the company of dogs, and if it is not, it will lead him to hell.

271
00:22:53,182 --> 00:22:58,131
When this was said, also near the naked dog ascetic wept and shed tears.

272
00:23:00,635 --> 00:23:04,321
And later, of course, in the discourse, they become disciples of the Buddha, you see.

273
00:23:06,105 --> 00:23:12,476
In the discourse, anybody who comes to ask the Buddha, it's very rare for them not to become a disciple.

274
00:23:12,496 --> 00:23:19,106
So, just in, if we were to sum up, there's this lovely word, osmosis.

275
00:23:20,200 --> 00:23:27,788
So in a chemical way, it's when one solvent passes through a semi-permeable membrane into another one.

276
00:23:27,888 --> 00:23:29,931
I think the salty one will...

277
00:23:31,472 --> 00:23:33,355
The water goes into the salty one.

278
00:23:33,494 --> 00:23:34,375
Is that right, Lorena?

279
00:23:34,395 --> 00:23:35,156
It was the other way around.

280
00:23:35,277 --> 00:23:35,817
It'll pass.

281
00:23:36,378 --> 00:23:40,864
They'll try and even each other out anyway.

282
00:23:40,884 --> 00:23:47,912
So what we have, it's also used figuratively, osmosis, was a gradual and unconscious assimilation of ideas and knowledges.

283
00:23:48,382 --> 00:23:51,226
And I think that's what's happening to us ever since we were born, you see.

284
00:23:51,807 --> 00:24:03,382
Is that without you knowing it, you take stuff in, you work with it from your own perspective, your own little experience of life, and then you give it out by the way you speak and the way you act and what you do.

285
00:24:04,202 --> 00:24:07,567
And this constant to and flow of things.

286
00:24:07,887 --> 00:24:10,471
So nothing is ever still, nothing is ever steady.

287
00:24:10,771 --> 00:24:11,772
And everything...

288
00:24:12,326 --> 00:24:40,173
if you think about it, everything that we have or experience is somewhere connected to other human beings and in that sense you can go back to this idea of Ubuntu where I am because of what you all are I am because of what we all are and we've lost that sense in the West because we've gone for individualism and that's unfortunate because

289
00:24:40,458 --> 00:24:44,864
We go around thinking that, you know, I do my own thing in my own way, in my own time.

290
00:24:45,345 --> 00:24:45,605
Yeah?

291
00:24:46,226 --> 00:24:51,334
That was the old hippie.

292
00:24:51,354 --> 00:25:00,185
So having sort of reflected on that, it's a case of recognizing that this flow is constantly going on.

293
00:25:00,386 --> 00:25:01,468
So that's what the Buddha says.

294
00:25:01,909 --> 00:25:05,012
To be aware of what... Ah, come in, Pam.

295
00:25:05,433 --> 00:25:08,337
To be aware of...

296
00:25:10,359 --> 00:25:18,636
what is internally happening, to be aware of what is externally happening, and to be aware internally and externally.

297
00:25:20,519 --> 00:25:25,089
So that's what he's asking us to do all the time in the discourse.

298
00:25:25,109 --> 00:25:29,719
And the discourse, although it's centered upon the actual practice of meditation,

299
00:25:30,172 --> 00:25:35,763
Remember, there's a whole section there about ordinary daily life, about how we behave in ordinary daily life.

300
00:25:35,784 --> 00:25:43,721
And when he does that, the same refrain comes through internally, externally, both internally and externally.

301
00:25:43,921 --> 00:25:47,429
And it's just making ourselves more and more aware of that.

302
00:25:47,449 --> 00:25:47,910
That's all.

303
00:25:49,595 --> 00:25:53,778
And the more aware you are of something, the more your choice is there.

304
00:25:55,121 --> 00:25:57,202
Now, it's not as though you've got free will.

305
00:25:58,002 --> 00:26:02,807
It's a conditioned choice because you know which way you're going to go.

306
00:26:02,847 --> 00:26:19,585
So for instance, if you decide to go for a walk and you've got your map, you've come to a crossroad, then you've got to figure out which road you take from that crossroad, especially if you've got multiple offshoots.

307
00:26:20,205 --> 00:26:27,477
So it's recognizing that and beginning to make the right decisions which draw us closer and closer to happiness.

308
00:26:27,636 --> 00:26:28,659
That's all we want to be, isn't it?

309
00:26:28,798 --> 00:26:29,480
A bit of happiness.

310
00:26:29,619 --> 00:26:31,702
Heaven's sake.

311
00:26:31,722 --> 00:26:44,442
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your practice of inwardly, outwardly, both inwardly and outwardly, will lead you to ultimate liberation sooner rather than later.

